Blue Plate is the bomb! The food is exceptional and is always consistent. The staff is always friendly and knowledgeable. I strongly recommend all those who have yet to dine here, to go. All of their dishes are to die but my all time favs are: the grilled romaine salad with baby tomatoes, avocado, pancetta and drizzled balsamic reduction on top, Rib Eye or NY Steak with Fries and of course last but not least the mac and cheese mkkay! The Focaccia to start is excellent as well!

Vibe was real cool with the open air viewable kitchen - though say goodnight to your clothes if you sit in the front dining room. The place is like someones house with odd blind corners and mysterious back room. The decor is fun and casual like an Anthropologie meets Urban Outfitters. And the food was quite good. Local Sardine bruchetta left you wanting more. I think all the apps did. This came with literally 3 fishies, though the flavor was explosive with just enough salt -from the tapenade. The crispy pork belly was really good but they only give you literally one square inch of action. There were also 4 to 5 mussels thrown in as a diversion but I didn't see the value of this dish. However, it was a tasty treat. The grilled Monterrey squid - pass. It was boring like a dish rag. I got the grilled porter house pork chop and was very happy with it. Didn't care too much for the cranberries that tasted like boiled prunes, but the chop itself was cooked to perfection. It was just one degree short of salmonella - excellent. Juicy, tasty, and the fatty burnt edges were so filthy. Paired with bitter brussel sprouts and rye spaetzle, good choices. I'd get this again.

The ever changing seasonal menu at The Blue Plate piqued my interest as I came back to have dinner with fellow Yelpers Jonathan W, Danny L, Jason G, and Jason W. There was still enough sunlight to keep the place well lit as we sat towards the back with a view of their gorgeous patio filled with greeneries and small tables. We had a reservation but the place wasn't packed like my last visit a few months ago. The small pieces of complimentary foccasia bread were served cold but still tasty, and we ordered three appetizers and five entrees to share. Our appetizers included Chicken Liver Pate ($8) which came with small pieces of stiff garlic toast served with liver pate, charred date, roasted cherry jam, and herb salad. The quality of the liver pate was thick and rich in flavor but next to the charred date the other items on the plate were cosmetic and not very useful. The Braised Spring Rabbit with Gnocchi ($20) was very delicious. There was a generous serving of tender meat layered with a combination of fava beans, pecorino crotonese, and chervil. Serving was outstanding and the pronounced garlic flavor could be a form of strength or setback depends on how one prefers it. We also had the Sardine Bruchetta ($15) which came with sardine nicely seasoned with white bean puree and nicoise olive tapenade layered on top of charred baguette. The prices listed here are different from the menu since the dishes were supersized to meet the needs of our group. For main entrees, Danny L and both Jasons ordered their signature Blue Plate Meatloaf which came with green beans and super delicious mashed potatoes. The meatloaf was well seasoned, flavorful, with good texture, and a dish that they seemed to carry all year round. Jonathan W's order of Painted Hills Ribeye ($28) arrived with French fries and smoked paprika aioli. The Ribeye wasn't as finesse as the one experienced at Mastro but the cut was very tender, well seasoned, and my favorite dish of the night. My order of Pork Porterhouse ($22) came with the bone intact and was bulky and humongous. The porterhouse was tender with a strong peppery flavor cooked into the meat with refried butter beans, pancetta, braised beans and grain mustard pork jus tucked underneath. The dish was mouthwatering but after a while it got a bit too peppery for my taste. For their June menu, I observed a range of bold and colorful flavors with a touch of no-none sense sophistication and comfort as each dish was fresh and cleanly executed. Comparing to the previous visit, service was less attentive and frequently absent even though the restaurant was less busy this time around. The strength of this restaurant has to be their range of selection in the menu with good food that comes with a decent level of complexity and on point execution. Aside from the service, I really enjoyed coming back to this charming restaurant to spend some time with friends. 4 stars for the overall experience.

My husband got the pork chop, and it was perfection. We will definitely be going back. The three small plates we shared, and it was enough to fill us both up.

One word: SMOKEOUT. I had high hopes walking in with my date. Casual, cozy, and the menu looking tasty. We had an early reservation so it was only half full which was fine by me since as others have noted the tables are really close together. Our waitress was not particularly friendly but the food and drinks came out in a timely manner. If anything, the dude who refilled our water and almost immediately brought over a new fork when the BF dropped his made up for her lack of sociability. I was really looking forward to the fried chicken this place is known for and while I enjoyed the buttermilk dressing/dip, the chicken itself was fairly bland and dry. Total bummer. Much better luck with the BF's prime rib which was seared perfectly and highly tasty. The potato gratin and housemade steak sauce hit the mark too. Now, you may be asking why just 1 star when the food and service weren't a complete disaster. Well, because the ventilation in the place was SO horrendous that there was literally a thick mist of smoke from the open kitchen that you could see and feel. Every time the cook(s) threw a piece of meat on the grill, it was like a smoke bomb had been detonated in the joint. The hostess cracked the door open to help alleviate the smog but it did little to help. The smoke was so ridiculously permeating it all but ruined the flavors and smell of our food. We could not finish our meal fast enough to get out into fresh air. I cannot even imagine what the restaurant must be like with a full house. Assuming this poor ventilation is the norm and not the result of an outstanding repair job, they better pray the Health Dept. doesn't show up for dinner one night. Talk about a health hazard.

I find this place a bit pricey for the food. It's like a fancy high end version of a "diner blue plate special" idea. The place is cozy, but its a bit noisy.

I'm sorry to have to say this, but Blue Plate is a must to avoid on any busy night. They just can't keep up with the orders. Valentine's Day dinner was a case in point. Reservations ran a full hour late, and the reservationist made no effort to warn people not to come on time. There's no place to wait and only a tiny doorway to stand in, so the crowd spilled out onto the street and stayed that way. The reservationist was very disorganized. I heard her snap at one couple: "Coming back and hanging around won't get you seated any sooner." They looked bewildered, "But you just called us and said our table was ready!" "Oh sorry... yes they're cleaning it up." I saw them still waiting about 30 minutes later when I came back. After we were seated (again, a full hour late), it took another 15 minutes before we could order, and another 1/2 hour after that before the appetizers came out. Those were quite nice, but the entrees weren't: both of ours were lukewarm to cold. Service was pleasant once we were seated, but the complete disorganization, hour-long wait and poorly heated dishes make it hard for me to give them more than 2 stars. On less crowded nights, the food is often 4 star worthy, but do yourself a favor: stay away on any night that may be busy. And call ahead to make sure they aren't running very very late.

    1/22/2010Previous review

    I have been saving this Yelp bookmark ever since reading about their bread pudding from Angella S. Recently I invited Angella to return to this place for dinner, and even though they no longer have bread pudding, the experience was splendid and remarkable.

    With artwork from local artists that features a wild bull at every turn, this place is quaint and unassuming with a large open kitchen by the front entrance. Although the seating area may look tiny at first, they also have a back dining room before you reach a beautiful garden patio towards the end of the restaurant. With dim lighting and a gorgeous venue, we were fortunate to arrive early to snag a table since those who came later all seemed to have a reservation.

    Appetizer: We shared the cauliflower soup and beet salad and it was very good. The cauliflower soup was thinly pureed embedded with cream and a delicate drizzle of oil and lightly seasoned. The salad came with thin pieces of beets with a firm texture covered with fresh watercress, crumbled goat cheese, and low acidic firm cara cara oranges with a mild dressing. I thought the beet salad was excellent.

    Main course: Our order of vegetable tart came with a delicious crust that resembled a pot pie smothered by maitake mushrooms and squash to the brim and covered with fresh frisee, pickled fennel supported by light oil and sauce. This dish was beautifully presented and I loved the cooked mushroom and squash combination and ways they intertwined with the fresh ingredients atop. Their red Zinfandel nicely complemented my meal.

    Dessert: Our mascarpone cheesecake and chocolate cake was absolutely divine. The mascarpone cheesecake was accompanied with a sprinkle of tiny oranges to provide a bittersweet accent with an equal amount of pistachios on the side. The warm chocolate cake came with a runny dark chocolate middle sitting on top of a fluffy whipped cream that carried a consistency which matches its oozing dark chocolate filling. We were living large by this point as we sipped our green tea while taking in these desserts in small bites--it was timeless. Even though I'm still craving bread pudding to this day, it was still quite a thrill.

    Their service was excellent and much appreciated. Our server, Adrianne, was one of the best that have ever assisted my table. I got there early and Adrianne was very kind to entertain me with warm focaccia and wine tasting until Angella arrives. Adrianne was also knowledgeable, attentive, and instrumental in orchestrating every phase of our meal with precision without being intrusive. Here, both food and service were equally excellent as this cute place exudes the quintessential elements to meet my expectations of a great restaurant. Since they change their menu frequently it just makes the place a whole lot more interesting. I would love to come back again.

    One of the best meals I've had in SF. Requested a seat in their very charming outdoor space, but was reminded that it would be cold after dark. Instead, they placed us right next to a window overseeing the outdoor space. Very accommodating. The food was terrific - very interesting combinations (candied kumquat next to crab ravioli, chorizo stuffed squid with a touch of honey and pepperoncini). Although the combinations were novel, the dishes never compromised flavor and execution in the name of being unique. Also,  we had waited a little longer than normal (really not by much) for our entrees, said nothing to our server about the wait, and still received a free drunken spanish goat cheese mac and cheese for the trouble. The price was also extremely reasonable given the food quality and atmosphere. Kudos to the blue plate team. This place is perfect for a date after sunset on bernal hill, or on just about any other occasion.

    Went to the Blue Plate for a friend's birthday tonight and was really impressed!  On the surface, the menu is deceptive in that the food almost appears to be your standard fare for a typical restaurant visit in this city.  
    But this is certainly not the case.  We ordered 5 appetizers, all of which were outstanding.  My favorites included the squid and the salmon.  Perfect.

    Amongst the 4 entrees were an impeccable fried chicken, a meatloaf that was unlike any I have ever tasted, and a fabulous macaroni that I am craving the recipe for...

    Dessert was an incredible chocolate cake, a brilliant butterscotch pudding (I normally despise butterscotch), and concord grape and green apple sorbets...

    Everything was perfect!
    Kudos to Executive Chef Sean Thomas for one of the best meals I have ever eaten!

    6/20/2009Previous review

    Interesting. In the 8 years I lived in San Francisco, I walked by this place many many times going to shows at the El Rio and never thought to check it out. I came back on my vacation and it was excellent.
    We started off the evening with the mushroom soup, which was quite tastey and dippable with the crusty bread that we were served with our appetizers. The Macaroni and cheese reminded me of some of the better restaurants I've eaten the same in the deep south. We did have the pleasure of being in the garden too, which was cool, but there were ample heaters that proved to be a good idea.
    After the appetizers, we decided to... have more appetizers! We ordered the calamari, which was impressive and cooked to perfection, the chard which was also excellent, and I got the IPA while my friend ordered a tastey red wine (I'm not a wine person, but she enjoyed it).
    Desert was a flawless bananna cream pie to die for.
    When we first got there at 6:30, there was hardly anyone there. By the time we left the place was packed and the word amongst the staff was that a party was coming in soon to take over the entire restaurant... You can't beat that!

    They offer free sparkling water as well as still water.  I'm a huge fan of sparkling water that just keeps appearing.  The corkage is still $15.

    12/11/2010

    I'm sorry to have to say this, but Blue Plate is a must to avoid on any busy night. They just can't keep up with the orders.

    Valentine's Day dinner was a case in point. Reservations ran a full hour late, and the reservationist made no effort to warn people not to come on time. There's no place to wait  and only a tiny doorway to stand in, so the crowd spilled out onto the street and stayed that way.

    The reservationist was very disorganized. I heard her snap at one couple: "Coming back and hanging around won't get you seated any sooner." They looked bewildered, "But you just called us and said our table was ready!" "Oh sorry... yes they're cleaning it up." I saw them still waiting about 30 minutes later when I came back.

    After we were seated (again, a full hour late), it took another 15 minutes before we could order, and another 1/2 hour after that before the appetizers came out. Those were quite nice, but the entrees weren't: both of ours were lukewarm to cold.

    Service was pleasant once we were seated, but the complete disorganization, hour-long wait and poorly heated dishes make it hard for me to give them more than 2 stars.

    On less crowded nights, the food is often 4 star worthy, but do yourself a favor: stay away on any night that may be busy. And call ahead to make sure they aren't running very very late.
